    <p>Sometimes, two factors will look similar but not be exactly the same. In particular, they will be negatives of each other.</p>
    
    <example>
      <title>Factors Differing by a Negative</title>
      <statement>
        <p>For example, consider,</p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\dfrac{2-x}{x-2}</mrow>
        </md>
        <p>The negative of <m>2-x</m> is <m>-(2-x) = -2+x = x-2</m>. If you divide a number and its negative (like e.g. 5 and <m>-5</m>), the result is always <m>-1</m>. We can factor out a <m>-1</m> from the numerator, and then cancel,</p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\amp = \dfrac{-(x-2)}{x-2} = \dfrac{-1}{1} = -1</mrow>
        </md>
      </statement>
    </example>
    
